Fashion & Style
| Special Report: Jewelry 
A New Generation for Alexandre Reza

By NAZANIN LANKARANIMAY 14, 2014



Continue reading the main story
Share This Page

Continue reading the main story









PARIS — After a long hiatus, Alexandre Reza, one of the most famous names in the Paris jewelry world, is making a comeback with a public show of jewelry — the company’s first in 20 years — which began at Sotheby’s in New York in the fall and is traveling to London; Doha, Qatar; and Beijing.Mr. Reza, of Iranian descent, was born into a jeweler’s family in Moscow in 1922. In 1925 they fled post-revolutionary Russia to France where he eventually started a jewelry and antiques business before gravitating to the gem trade. He is retired now, but he made a fortune as a gem merchant and along the way built an exceptional collection of colored gemstones and diamonds.In the 1960s and ’70s he was a principal supplier to the Parisian jewelers on the Place Vendôme, before discovering his own affinity for design.He set up shop on the Place Vendôme in the 1980s. Olivier Reza, his son, said: “My father acquired a number of Parisian jewelry ateliers and used their savoir-faire to create pieces of his own design. With that, he created his own brand.”

Advertisement

Continue reading the main story

Olivier, now 40, left a banking career in New York in 2008 to take over the company after his father’s retirement the year before. At the time, the business was in the doldrums, still reeling from a series of robberies in the previous 15 years, and he found himself confronting some strategic decisions. Continue reading the main story







Advertisement

Continue reading the main story





His basic options were to sell the inventory and abandon the brand, or to find a way to carry on. To understand the value of the family business, Olivier Reza had to evaluate the inventory, the house’s history, and the wealth of drawings and records in the company’s archives.Having excluded the idea of selling, he had to come up with a revival strategy. To start, he decided to shrink the business, closing its five stores worldwide.
Photo






A “rose perlée” necklace designed by Alexandre Reza in 1996. It has a yellow diamond at its center and five strands of natural pearls.

Credit
            Courtesy of Alexandre Reza        


“The real métier of haute joaillerie, as it was established by Louis Cartier, Frédéric Boucheron, Laurence Graff, Jacques Arpels and my father, draws primarily on passion,” Olivier Reza said in an interview in the ornate first-floor salons of the 18th-century Hôtel de Fontpertuis that the jeweler occupies on the Place Vendôme. “Practically, that means you must be able to invest tens of millions in precious stones and really believe in what you are doing.“After the war, my father was able to purchase quantities of natural and untreated stones in Ceylon and Burma,” he said, referring to today’s Sri Lanka and Myanmar. “The Reza house currently possesses one of the world’s largest inventories of unheated and untreated colored gemstones. When you sit on a fortune like that, you need vision and passion, and you cannot be in a hurry.”He added: “We liberated ourselves from retail pressure to concentrate on creation. Now we have the luxury of time and can take eight to 12 months to produce a piece without worrying about the rent.” The firm has spent three years designing a new collection with a team of four, outsourcing production to three workshops here. The show that represents the culmination of his efforts mixes old and new. It includes 25 historic pieces from the past 40 years, showcasing the stones and craftsmanship that made Alexandre Reza a celebrated name. There are 15 new pieces in a more contemporary style, “mostly unique, that, creatively speaking, were made from scratch,” Olivier Reza said. “Through that process, I have realized I have a preference for geometric shapes.”
