Alexandre Reza “was a connoisseur of high-quality stones and brought many exceptional ones to France,” said Marguerite de Cerval, a jewelry historian in Paris. “His technique remained traditional but he had a style and flair that appealed to an international clientele.”The house was particularly known for parures and the show includes several matching pieces, notably a set featuring 102 carats of untreated Colombian emeralds and earrings set with 145 carats of Ceylon sapphires and diamonds.“Some of the parures have 20 stones of over 10 carats each, all in the same color,” Olivier Reza said.Alexandre Reza also made a specialty of “trembleuse,” or articulated, jewelry. A 52-carat Burmese sapphire ring, set atop 101 diamonds, is a striking example of his work: “The mount is invisible, you see only the diamonds,” his son said.

Advertisement

Continue reading the main story

“Alexandre used to say that the stone drove jewelry design,” Ms. de Cerval said. “Some of Olivier’s designs are innovative but others remain on his father’s path. It remains to be seen whether he will succeed in departing from the house’s traditional formulas.”
Continue reading the main story






