VOGUE GIOIELLO|Designer|A new twist
A new twist
Alexandre Reza returns to the Biennale as a sign of renewal









Share!Tagalexandre reza - olivier reza
















/



Alexandre Reza, 1980 -  Brooch with a 133.64 ct. Ceylon sapphire, white and yellow diamonds, drop-cut sapphires. Photo courtesy press officeOlivier Reza -  Blackened white gold Trembleur earrings with diamonds and rubies. Photo courtesy press officeAlexandre Reza, 1979 -  Bracelet with a 3.12 ct. emerald, 10 D Flawless diamonds, 95 pear-shaped diamonds. Photo courtesy press officeOlivier Reza -  Pink gold Farandoles earrings with spinels and diamonds. Photo courtesy press officeAlexandre Reza -  Showing an exceptional necklace of D Internally Flawless diamonds. Photo courtesy press officeOlivier Reza -  Pendant earrings with two oval Ceylon sapphires and diamonds. Photo courtesy press officeAlexandre Reza, 1975 -  Diamond chocker with Ceylon sapphires. Photo courtesy press officeOlivier Reza -  White gold Solo Aerès ring with a 10.07 ct. pear-cut D Flawless diamon. Photo courtesy press officeOlivier Reza -  Platinum ring with a 9.88 ct. emerald-cut diamond and two half-moon Colombian emeralds. Photo courtesy press officeOlivier Reza -  Photo courtesy press officeAlexandre Reza, 1998 -  Manhattan earrings with 2 Colombian emeralds, 2 cushion-cut yellow diamonds and white diamonds.  . Photo courtesy press office<>










Imperceptible yet undeniable signs of continuity are the hallmarks of the collections by this jewelry dynasty that has decided to return to the Biennale des Antiquaires after 14 years (though it has participated three times in the past). Alexandre Reza has a refined knowledge of rare, precious gems, and it is his name on the famous boutique in Place Vendôme. The torch has been passed to his son Olivier, who worked by his father’s side from the time he was a child. In an important moment of change and affirmation, the Biennale represents a significant step along a new path, the first time the spotlight has been shone on the brand internationally since its relaunch 18 months ago. Olivier Reza worked for four years on the creation of about 30 luxurious pieces inspired by the world of art, by Henri Matisse’s paintings and Robert Lazzarini sculptures. The collection also features pieces that fully embody Alexandre Reza’s philosophy, which seeks out beauty with extremely high quality stones, excellent manufacture and a recognizable style – and brought up to date with a more contemporary feel in terms of creativity. It’s natural to compare the masterpieces of yesterday and today to come to the conclusion that they are products of the same philosophy in terms of the size of the jewels, the same attention to the proportions of the stone and the same use of the most sophisticated working methods like the “en tremblant” technique carried out by the father and now the son to offer a bit of movement to the individual pieces that bring a jewel to life.

                di Maristella Campi
                    Published: 11/17/2014 - 07:00







